---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import OrnamentalDivider from '../components/OrnamentalDivider.astro';
import Embers from '../components/Embers.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Valtiare"
  description="Valtiare is a whimsydark universe of handmade art and short fiction by Matt Gilbert. Every image here is made by hand."
>
  <article>
    <header class="relative mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 pt-24 pb-2 text-center">
      <Embers />
      <div class="relative">
        <p class="mb-6 font-sans text-[0.65rem] uppercase tracking-[0.32em] text-stone-500">
          About the Universe
        </p>
        <OrnamentalDivider class="mx-auto mb-10 w-36 text-brass-600" />
        <h1 class="heading-rule mx-auto font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl text-parchment-50">
          Handmade in the dark
        </h1>
        <OrnamentalDivider class="mx-auto mt-12 w-36 text-brass-600" />
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[640px] px-6 py-16">
      <div class="prose-whimsy">
        <p>
          <em>Valtiare</em> is a whimsydark art and fiction universe made by
          hand — painted miniatures, sculpted models, dioramas, watercolors,
          ink drawings, maps, and the short fictions that grow up around them.
          What you read here are the stories the characters remember
          afterward. What you see are the pieces that survived the telling.
        </p>

        <p>
          The artwork is always made the slow way. Primer, basecoat, wash,
          highlight, glaze. Pencil, then ink, then patience. Nothing on this
          site is generated by a machine, and nothing ever will be. If a piece
          looks strange, it was made strangely, by a person, on purpose.
        </p>

        <p>
          Many of the stories emerge from tabletop roleplaying campaigns —
          long, quiet games with friends, in which characters say things that
          refuse to be forgotten. The gameplay stays at the table. What ends
          up here is what was worth carrying home.
        </p>

        <h2>About the work</h2>

        <p>
          I'm Matt Gilbert. I paint miniatures, write fiction, run
          tabletop games, and tend a small cabinet of projects that all orbit
          the same warm-dark aesthetic. Valtiare is where the fiction and the
          finished art live together.
        </p>

        <p>
          For miniature painting tutorials and related work, there's
          <em>The&nbsp;Hobbinomicon</em>. For everything else — the broader
          creative ecosystem and whatever else is happening on a given day —
          there's <a href="https://mattglbrt.com">mattglbrt.com</a>.
        </p>

        <p>
          This site is intentionally small, quiet, and slow to update. Nothing
          is sold here. Nothing is tracked beyond the basic server logs. If
          you'd like to follow along, there's an
          <a href="/rss.xml">RSS feed</a> — the old reliable.
        </p>

        <h2>A note on the tone</h2>

        <p>
          Whimsydark isn't grimdark. There's warmth in the darkness here.
          Candlelight, old prayer, small kept things. Grief that remembers it
          was once affection. If you walk a page and leave feeling both a
          little sadder and a little more awake, the work is doing what it's
          supposed to do.
        </p>
      </div>

      <OrnamentalDivider class="mx-auto mt-16 w-40 text-brass-600" />
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
